## String

Declare a string by wrapping a variable's value in single or double quotes:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign my_string = "Hello World!" %}
{% endraw %}
```

### String interpolation

{% include 'alert/note', content: 'This feature requires the `string_interpolation: true` flag in `config.yml`. See [Single vs double quotes](#single-vs-double-quotes) for details.' %}

Double-quoted strings support interpolation using the {% raw %}`{{ }}`{% endraw %} syntax. This lets you embed variables, property access, and filters directly inside strings:

#### Input

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign name = "Alice" %}
{% assign greeting = "Hello {{ name }}!" %}
{{ greeting }}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
Hello Alice!
```

Interpolation supports filter chains, multiple expressions, and all variable access patterns:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign first = "Alice" %}
{% assign last = "Smith" %}
{% assign full_name = "{{ first }} {{ last | upcase }}" %}
{{ full_name }}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
Alice SMITH
```

String interpolation works in all tags that accept string values — `assign`, `function`, `log`, `background`, `export`, and others:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign var = "world" %}
{% log "hello {{ var }}" %}
{% function res = "lib/func", arg: "hello {{ var }}" %}
{% endraw %}
```

### Single vs double quotes

Single-quoted strings **never** interpolate. Use single quotes when you need literal {% raw %}`{{ }}`{% endraw %} text:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign name = "Alice" %}
{% assign interpolated = "Hello {{ name }}" %}
{% assign literal = 'Hello {{ name }}' %}
{{ interpolated }}
{{ literal }}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
Hello Alice
Hello {{ name }}
```

{% include 'alert/note', content: 'String interpolation is enabled by default on new instances. On existing instances it must be enabled explicitly by adding `string_interpolation: true` to your `config.yml`, as it can potentially break your site — any double-quoted strings containing literal `{{ }}` text will start being interpolated.' %}

## Number

Numbers include floats and integers:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign my_int = 25 %}
{% assign my_float = 39.756 %}
{% endraw %}
```
## Boolean

Booleans are either `true` or `false`. No quotations are necessary when declaring a boolean:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign foo = true %}
{% assign bar = false %}
{% endraw %}
```
## Nil

Nil is a special empty value that is returned when Liquid code has no results. It is not a string with the characters `nil`.

Nil is treated as `false` in the conditions of if blocks and other Liquid tags that check the truthfulness of a statement.

In the following example, if the user does not exist (that is, user returns nil), Liquid will not print the greeting:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% if user %}
  Hello {{ user.name }}!
{% endif %}
{% endraw %}
```

Tags or outputs that return nil will not print anything to the page.

#### Input

```liquid
{% raw %}
The current user is {{ user.name }}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
The current user is
```

## Hash (Object)

Hash represents an object as a key value dictionary, allowing a value to be another Hash. The most used object is [context - a built-in global object](/api-reference/liquid/platformos-objects#context)

### Initializing a new object

Use the `assign` tag with a hash literal:

{% raw %}
```liquid
  {% assign my_object = { "hello": "world" } %}
```
{% endraw %}

You can include nested hashes, arrays, and variables as values:

{% raw %}
```liquid
  {% assign name = "Alice" %}
  {% assign my_object = { "greeting": "hello", "user": name, "tags": ["admin", "editor"] } %}
```
{% endraw %}

### Accessing object attributes

To access a value of an object, you can use dot notation or if you would like to use variables instead of hardcoded key, you could use [] notation.

#### Input

```liquid
{% raw %}
{{ my_object.hello }}
{%- assign var = 'hello' -%}
{{ my_object[val] }}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
world
world
```

### Working with an object

  You can extend objects using the `assign` tag with bracket or dot notation:

  ```liquid
{% raw %}
  {% assign my_object = {} %}
  {% assign my_object["new_key"] = "value" %}
  {% assign my_object.another_key = "another value" %}
{% endraw %}
  ```

  Another useful way to extend an object is by merging two objects, which can be accomplished with [hash_merge filter](/api-reference/liquid/platformos-filters#hash-merge).

  If you need to perform certain operation on object, most likely there is already implemented [platformOS filter](/api-reference/liquid/platformos-filters) for that with `hash_` prefix.

## Array

Arrays hold lists of variables of any type.

### Accessing items in arrays

To access all the items in an array, you can loop through each item in the array using an iteration tag.

#### Input

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign users = ["Tobi", "Laura", "Tetsuro", "Adam"] %}
{% for user in users %}
  {{ user }}
{% endfor %}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
Tobi Laura Tetsuro Adam
```

### Accessing specific items in arrays

You can use square bracket `[` `]` notation to access a specific item in an array. Array indexing starts at zero.

#### Input

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign site = { "users": ["Tobi", "Laura", "Tetsuro", "Adam"] } %}
{{ site.users[0] }}
{{ site.users[1] }}
{{ site.users[3] }}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
Tobi
Laura
Adam
```

### Initializing arrays

Use the `assign` tag with an array literal:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign arr = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"] %}
{% assign empty_arr = [] %}
{% endraw %}
```

You can also use the `split` filter to break a string into an array of substrings:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign arr = '1,2,3,4,5' | split: ',' %}
{{ arr }} => [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
{% endraw %}
```

To append elements, use the `<<` operator:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign arr = [] %}
{% assign arr << "first" %}
{% assign arr << "second" %}
{{ arr }} => ["first", "second"]
{% endraw %}
```

### Searching in arrays

#### contains

You can check for the presence of a substring in a string, but `contains` can also check for the presence of a string in an array of strings. You can use it only for searching strings. You cannot use it to check for an object in an array of objects.

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% comment %} site.users = ["Tobi", "Laura", "Tetsuro", "Adam"] {% endcomment %}
{% if site.users contains 'Tobi' %}
  Tobi is in users.
{% endif %}
{% endraw %}
```

#### any
You can check if the given array contains at least one of the queried string/number.

##### params

- array (Array) - array to search in - default: []
- query (StringNumber) - String/Number compared to each item in the given array - default: 'true'

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% comment %} site.users = ["Tobi", "Laura", "Tetsuro", "Adam"] {% endcomment %}
{% if site.users | any: 'Tobi' %}
  Tobi is in users.
{% endif %}
{% endraw %}
```

## Truthy and falsy values

In programming, anything that returns true in a conditional is called truthy. Anything that returns false in a conditional is called falsy. All object types can be described as either truthy or falsy.

### Truthy

All values in Liquid are truthy except nil and false.

In the example below, the string “Tobi” is not a boolean, but it is truthy in a conditional:

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% assign tobi = "Tobi" %}

{% if tobi %}
  This condition will always be true.
{% endif %}
{% endraw %}
```

Strings, even when empty, are truthy. The example below will result in empty HTML tags if `settings.fp_heading` is empty:

#### Input

```liquid
{% raw %}
{% if settings.fp_heading %}
  <h1>{{ settings.fp_heading }}</h1>
{% endif %}
{% endraw %}
```

#### Output

```liquid
<h1></h1>
```

### Falsy

The falsy values in Liquid are `nil` and `false`.

